Fall Sports Update: We are planning to move forward with a fall season for Lawrence High School varsity sports. We will begin by staggering practices and will follow rules set by the NJ State Interscholastic Athletic Association (NJSIAA). Football and field hockey practices may begin September 11th, for heat acclimation purposes, and practices for other fall sports may begin September 14th.

Head coaches will hold virtual Town Halls next week to provide more information for interested athletes and their parents. We will share those dates and times with you soon.

Questions? Please contact the head coach (https://tinyurl.com/LHSFallSports2020) or the Athletic Office at (609) 671-5516 x2650.

post_text:
We are proud to announce that all seven of our schools achieved Bronze Certification status (for the second time!) as awarded by the Sustainable Jersey for Schools organization! Schools maintain this status for three years.

Our district has a Green Team and each school has a Green Team leader. Cari Gallagher, Lawrenceville Elementary third grade teacher, leads the district Green Team. Certified schools and their district receive priority consideration in the Sustainable Jersey for Schools Grant Program. Our district has applied for and received multiple grants from this program for our environmental efforts.

Certified schools and their district receive priority consideration in the Sustainable Jersey for Schools Grant Program. Our district has applied for and received multiple grants from this program for our environmental efforts.

post_text: Today, the Board of Ed approved a new calendar for the 20-21 school year. The changes on the previously adopted calendar include the movement of the October and November professional development days for staff to the start of the school year so that students would begin on September 8th rather than September 3rd. Additionally, the district will be closed for Juneteenth on June 18th which was recently approved as a state holiday (3rd Friday in June). The previous calendar had an additional closure day on May 28th which was swapped with June 18th so as to not extend the calendar.

Can you hear me now? Not on Monday, August 24th!

LTPS is getting a new phone system. Starting about 9 AM today, we will take down our old phone system prior to moving over to the new system. We will have no phone service, for incoming or outgoing calls, during this time. We hope to have the new phone system up and running no later than 1 PM today

The 2018 Referendum approved by Lawrence voters included a provision for a new phone system, one of the safety measures included in the bond issue.

post_text:
Have you completed the 2020 Census? If not, it’s safe and easy to complete it online, by phone, or by mail! The US Census Bureau’s recent decision to end data collection prematurely, by September 30 instead of October 31, jeopardizes the future of millions of children and youth by undercounting the population and shortchanging the funding of federal programs for a decade or more.

Read why Child Trends (https://tinyurl.com/yyvmhqc3) opposes this decision and calls for the Bureau to continue data collection until all households can be counted. And if you haven’t already, please complete the 2020 Census here!
https://tinyurl.com/y6aqcj52

post_text:
Thank you to the Lawrence Health Department’s COVID-19 team for working nonstop to flatten the curve in Lawrence! The team includes two public health nurses, five LTPS school nurses, and one Rockstar intern, Rabiah Asif.

Rabiah is a Lawrence High graduate with a Master's degree in public health from Rutgers. She has worked tirelessly compiling mandatory reports, tying up loose ends, and troubleshooting the sometimes confusing case investigation/contact tracing software for the rest of the team.

Thank you to Rabiah, and the whole Lawrence Health Department COVID-19 team! We truly appreciate the job that our health professionals are doing in Lawrence to keep us safe in this town and around the state.

post_text:
As Superintendent Kasun mentioned at the July 22nd special board of education meeting, the date for school to start for students in September is changing from September 3rd to September 8th, the day after Labor Day.

The first day for staff to return remains the same on September 1st. Two professional development (PD) days were already planned for staff for September 1st and 2nd. In the planned, revised calendar, the October 12th and November 4th PD days will be moved to September 3rd and 4th. Thus, September 1 – 4 will be four PD days for staff.

October 12th and November 4th will be regular school days for staff and students.

The first day for staff to return remains the same on September 1st. Two professional development (PD) days were already planned for staff for September 1st and 2nd. In the planned, revised calendar, the October 12th and November 4th PD days will be moved to September 3rd and 4th. Thus, September 1 – 4 will be four PD days for staff.

October 12th and November 4th will be regular school days for staff and students.

We’re looking forward to seeing the Class of 2020 one last time at their final celebration…the in-person graduation. This special event is set for Wednesday, July 29 at 10 AM at the Lawrence High School (LHS) football stadium. The rain date is July 30th.

In order to attend, members of the Class of 2020 must register and request tickets by Friday, July 17 using the Google Form sent to graduates via their email accounts.

On the 29th, seniors should arrive at the LHS cafeteria veranda by 9 AM and bring their yearbooks. They will have the opportunity to sign classmates’ yearbooks before the graduation ceremony.

As we observe Independence Day over the coming weekend, The U.S. Census Bureau is aiming to make the celebration even greater. Before the fireworks begin, you will have an opportunity to win $5000 by putting your Census-related knowledge on display. Download the popular HQ Trivia app and join #HQTrivia and #2020Census at 9pm ET Saturday for the first-ever Census-themed trivia challenge. The game takes about 10 minutes, roughly the same time needed to complete your 2020 Census online. Good luck and enjoy!

Have you completed your Census yet? Data gathered in the Census helps determine how much funding and services our school district and Lawrence municipality get. Take it here: https://2020census.gov/

Bee safe and enjoy the 4th of July weekend!

Today is Juneteenth, the day that celebrates the emancipation of slaves in Texas on June 19th, 1865, two and half years after Abraham Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation. The holiday, whose name is derived from a combination of June and nineteen, is also called “Juneteenth Independence Day,” “Freedom Day,” or “Emancipation Day.” Read more about the history of Juneteenth here.
https://nmaahc.si.edu/blog-post/historical-legacy-juneteenth

It was somewhat of a festive atmosphere in front of Lawrence High School today. Staff from throughout the district and a few community members participating in Adopt-a-Senior arrived at the school to pick up their bag(s) to deliver to a senior that they “adopted.” Cars lined up in front of the school at their designated pick-up time. The Lawrence Township Education Association provided the bags containing the student’s cap and gown, 2 tickets to the June 19 graduation photo op, a large towel from the Project Graduation Committee, and certificates from Moe’s and dorm.com. Those adopting a senior also provided their adoptee with a small gift to celebrate their success as they end their high school career. LHS Senior Class Advisor Tara Huber organized the special recognition.

post_text: June 9th is Donald Duck’s birthday! National Donald Duck Day celebrates the funny animated cartoon character who made his first screen debut on June 9, 1934 in The Wise Little Hen. During Donald’s second appearance in Orphan’s Benefit, he introduced his comic friend, Mickey Mouse. Donald’s girlfriend, Daisy Duck, along with his nephews, Huey, Dewey, and Louie, were introduced shortly after that and the rest is history!. #DonaldDuckDay

post_text: On May 20th, National Rescue Dog Day recognizes all the benefits of allowing a four-legged canine to adopt you into their life. According to the ASPCA, approximately 3.3 million dogs enter shelters every year. When these abandoned and abused animals find their way to a shelter, each one needs a forever home and their potential is limitless. When it comes to four-legged friends, rescue dogs improve the human condition by leaps and bounds, barks, and yips. Give them a treat! Contact your local shelter to see how you can help. #NationalRescueDogDay

post_text: Observed annually on May 19th, National Devil’s Food Cake Day is enjoyed by chocolate cake lovers throughout the country and around the world. Despite its name, Devil’s Food Cake is a heavenly chocolate cake. Its recipe differs from a regular chocolate cake, using hot or boiling water as the primary liquid and cocoa instead of chocolate. Celebrate and whip one up today! #DevilsFoodCakeDay

post_text: May 15th is National Chocolate Chip Day! Have you ever wondered how a single ingredient would change a recipe? If it weren’t for Ruth Graves Wakefield, a curious baker working at the Toll House Inn in 1937, we wouldn’t have chocolate chips! Ruth added cut up chunks of a Nestles semi-sweet chocolate bar to her cookie recipe, which now appears as the Toll House Cookie recipe on packages of Nestles chocolate morsels. Thank you, Ruth! #ChocolateChipDay

post_text: May 14th is National Dance Like a Chicken Day! Written in the 1950s by Werner Thomas, a Swiss accordionist, the Chicken Dance didn’t even make it to the United States until sometime in the 1970s. Upon arriving in America, the song acquired choreography with repetitive beak, wing, and tail motions, as well as the new name, The Chicken Dance. So today, have some fun and dance like a chicken. Be silly. Be erratic. Do The Chicken Dance! #DanceLikeAChickenDay

post_text:
May 13th is National Apple Pie Day! The first apple pie recipe printed was in England in 1381. The list of ingredients included good apples, good spices, figs, raisins, pears, saffron, and cofyn (a type of pastry crust).

While the apple pie existed well before the Pilgrims landed on the eastern shores of what is now The United States, Americans wax poetic about how American apple pie is. The phrase “as American as apple pie” has been around for more than 100 years. #NationalApplePieDay

post_text:
May 12th is National Fibromyalgia Awareness Day. Fibromyalgia is a musculoskeletal syndrome and causes a variety of symptoms, including widespread pain, tender points, and chronic fatigue. It affects more than 12 million Americans.

The first National Fibromyalgia Awareness Day was observed in 1992 in honor of the birthday of Florence Nightingale. Historical documentation suggests Nightingale may have suffered from symptoms similar to fibromyalgia and chronic fatigue.Learn more at www.fmcpaware.org.
#FibromyalgiaAwarenessDay

From the NJDOE:
In New Jersey, we celebrate the second week in May as “Special Education Week” – a designation that has been memorialized in state statute.This week recognizes the contributions of students, parents, teachers, child study team members, administrators and school board members in their efforts to ensure educational access and equity for students with disabilities. In New Jersey, more than 241,000 children receive special education instruction and services in public and private schools.

The theme for this year’s Special Education Week, is “Creating, Learning, Growing.” Since 1985, the New Jersey School Boards Association (NJSBA) and ASAH, an organization representing private special education schools, have sponsored Special Education Week in New Jersey and have also led a poster contest for students intended to highlight student achievements. Additional resources to support districts, educators and families are available on the NJDOE’s Special Education webpage. https://www.state.nj.us/education/specialed/

post_text:
Today is National Space Day! In celebration, Public Consulting Group (PCG) is excited to announce the launch of a free online space program, beginning with a project created in partnership with the Aldrin Family Foundation, ShareSpace Education, and NASA.

We Came in Peace: The Apollo Visitor Complex Project is a team activity that invites families to imagine a time when people travel to the moon for vacation, visiting lunar landing sites from NASA’s Apollo missions. In this unique program, families work together to research, report, design, construct, and present a visitor complex for people visiting the lunar landing sites. Your team will create a video that will be shared with others in an online learning community, Pepper™ to win prizes and share with other aspiring astronauts. Learn more and get ready to launch: https://tinyurl.com/ya7pw2f5

Each year, National Adopt a Shelter Pet Day on April 30th raises awareness for thousands of pets that are waiting for (and needing) adoption from shelters. Animal shelters require year-round assistance and adoption is a part of the process. Even though most shelters are closed to walk-ins right now, many are still arranging for adoptions and donations. Contact the Humane Society or your local shelter to see how you can help! #AdoptAShelterPet
https://www.humanesociety.org/

post_text:
April 28 is National Superhero Day, honoring superheroes both real and fictional. Batman, Superman, Captain America, Wonder Woman, Iron Man, Hulk, and Spiderman are just some of the fictional superheroes whose names we recognize as great role models for our children. They serve and protect while fighting evil.

Real-life superheroes may not have superpowers or wear capes, but they are also great role models who serve and protect while fighting evil. Healthcare workers, military personnel, police officers, firefighters, and teachers are just a few of the heroes who protect us on a daily basis. Here’s to the superheroes on #NationalSuperheroDay!

post_text:
Lawrence High senior Arjun Agarwal is in the LTPS news once again! A Cardinal high five to Arjun for being named a Governor’s Scholar and being “…selected from a very talented pool of applicants to participate in this summer's Governor's School of Engineering & Technology hosted by the Rutgers University School of Engineering!”

Additional excerpts from his congratulatory letter:
“. . . . You will be spending four weeks, free of charge to you and your family, engaged in engineering and technology with others who share your interests.. . . . This summer's Governor's School of Engineering & Technology has been made possible through very generous sponsorship by Rutgers University, the State of New Jersey, corporate donors, Governor's School alumni, and a number of other donors.”

“This summer, scholars will be taking 4 academic online classes, completing a virtual research and/or design project in a group of 4 - 5 students, and meeting equally talented peers and professionals from across the state.” Congrats, Arjun!

April is Autism Awareness Month. post_text: April 22, 2020 will mark 50 years of Earth Day! The theme for Earth Day 2020 is climate action. On April 22, 1970, 20 million Americans — 10% of the U.S. population at the time — took to the streets, college campuses and hundreds of cities to protest environmental ignorance and demand a new way forward for our planet. The first Earth Day is credited with launching the modern environmental movement, and is now recognized as the planet’s largest civic event. Learn more at www.earthday.org. #EarthDay #NationalEarthDay

Observed annually on April 17, National Haiku Poetry Day encourages all to try their hand in creativity. Haiku poetry is a form of Japanese poetry that is non-rhyming and usually consists of 3 lines with a syllable pattern of 5-7-5. Usually, an element of nature, a season, moment of beauty, or an individual experience inspires haiku poems. Sensory language is used to capture a feeling, image or moment, as is this poem by Richard Wright from “Haiku: This Other World.”

Whitecaps on the bay:
A broken signboard banging
In the April wind.

Celebrate today by creating a haiku poem of your own! #NationalHaikuPoetryDay

post_text: Each year on April 15th, National Titanic Remembrance Day is dedicated to the memory of more than 1500 lives lost when the Titanic sank into the icy waters of the North Atlantic Ocean in April 1912. Known as the “the unsinkable ship,” the Titanic hit an iceberg at 11:40 pm on April 14,1912, on her maiden voyage from England to New York City and sank on April 15. Those who perished did so mainly due to an insufficient number of lifeboats on board the ship. Have 3 hours and 15 minutes to spare? Consider observing the day by watching the 1997 film, "Titanic." #TitanicRemembranceDay

post_text: April 13th is National Scrabble Day! Originally named Lexiko and then Criss-Cross Words, Alfred Mosher Butts eventually settled on the name Scrabble. The amateur artist and unemployed architect developed the word game in the midst of the depression but it wasn’t until 1948 that Butts finally began to produce the game with the name Scrabble. Rainy days and Scrabble are a perfect combination! #NationalScrabbleDay

Looking for additional things to do with your children?
Big names, and usual competitors, across education, technology and media came together to create a free, one-stop-shop site for education resources for K-12 students, teachers, and parents.

Go to https://WideOpenSchool.org

On the site, students will see an interactive daily schedule customized to their age range, a list of live virtual events like storytimes and concerts, and links to materials for every school subject, all available for free and vetted for quality by Common Sense. The suggested schedule is updated daily with new activities and lessons, and the developers will continue to add to the site as they discover more content and new partners join the project. Some materials are also available in Spanish, and organizers said they are working to add more non-English resources.

Live virtual events: https://wideopenschool.org/live-events/?audience=family&program-type=live-events&grade-range=prek-5

March 30th is National Virtual Vacation Day, reminding us all to relax, recharge, and rejuvenate no matter where we are. Virtual vacations don’t require money, packing, or transcontinental flights. All you need to achieve a virtual vacation is your imagination and free virtual reality (VR) apps or a VR headset.

Enjoy an exciting African safari or hike the exotic Amazon rainforest. Then hit the beach in Bali, or join in the festivities at Mardi Gras. Explore a space vacation if you dare!

There’s never been a better time than now to explore a virtual vacation. Here are some VR tours to get you started!
https://nationaldaycalendar.com/virtual-reality-tours/
#VirtualVacationDay #LawrenceStrong

post_text:
We received the following from the NJ Department of Education today:

Given the continued threat of the Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) to our school communities and the resulting school closures, Governor Phil Murphy today announced that the State of New Jersey is canceling all statewide student assessments for the spring 2020 testing window. This includes the springtime administration of the New Jersey Student Learning Assessments (NJSLA), ACCESS for ELLs, and the Dynamic Learning Maps (DLM) assessment. The state is working to mitigate any unintended consequences of canceling the spring assessment, and will work through multiple channels to keep stakeholders fully informed of updated guidance and other changes.

We received the following from the NJ Department of Education today:

Given the continued threat of the Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) to our school communities and the resulting school closures, Governor Phil Murphy today announced that the State of New Jersey is canceling all statewide student assessments for the spring 2020 testing window. This includes the springtime administration of the New Jersey Student Learning Assessments (NJSLA), ACCESS for ELLs, and the Dynamic Learning Maps (DLM) assessment. The state is working to mitigate any unintended consequences of canceling the spring assessment, and will work through multiple channels to keep stakeholders fully informed of updated guidance and other changes.

post_text: We’ve seen on various local social media sites postings about Lawrence members of our collective family wanting to help provide food for some students while our district is closed. Kind gestures such as this are heartwarming and are what make our Lawrence community a special place. Please know that our district has lunches covered for our students in the free or reduced meal program. We have worked out logistics with Maschios, our food service, so we can continue to serve those children during the closure. Thank you for your kind thoughts and gestures. Perhaps other agencies in town can distribute any planned donations to those in need. Best wishes for staying healthy!

post_text: Our Board of Education (BOE) and audience members were treated to musical performances at the BOE’s Feb. 12 monthly meeting. Fourth graders Harrison Petrick and Serrajas Elayda played piano pieces, Piyush Nawade (8th) performed on the bass, and Aidan Sim (6th) played a piece on the cello. The performances were in recognition and celebration of the BOE’s receiving the New Jersey Music Educators Association’s 2020 Outstanding School Board Award for their support of music education. Melissa Clark, Intermediate and Middle School music teacher, coordinated nominating the BOE and submitting the extensive application. Bravo!
text: Our Board of Education (BOE) and audience members were treated to musical performances at the BOE’s Feb. 12 monthly meeting. Fourth graders Harrison Petrick and Serrajas Elayda played piano pieces, Piyush Nawade (8th) performed on the bass, and Aidan Sim (6th) played a piece on the cello. The performances were in recognition and celebration of the BOE’s receiving the New Jersey Music Educators Association’s 2020 Outstanding School Board Award for their support of music education. Melissa Clark, Intermediate and Middle School music teacher, coordinated nominating the BOE and submitting the extensive application. Bravo!

post_text:
We’re honored that Mel Leipzig, globally-known realist painter, continues painting ‘Life at Lawrence High School” (LHS). Mel has dedicated his career to painting people in their environments. Below is his current piece at LHS.

Mel’s works are part of the permanent collections at the Whitney Museum of American Art, the Yale Art Gallery, the National Academy Museum, Cooper Hewitt Museum, New Jersey State Museum, and the White House Collection in Washington, D.C. In 2006, he was elected to the National Academy of Design in New York. View some of Mel’s works done outside of LHS. https://www.melleipzig.com/

post_text:
What’s up with February 18? Schools open or closed?

Schools are closed Monday, February 17 for the Presidents’ Day holiday.

February 18 is an Emergency Closing Day built into the school calendar to use as a make-up day in the event we closed schools for inclement weather or another reason. We have missed no days of school in this school year thus far. If we don’t have a closure between now and Tuesday, February 18 (weather can bring surprises!), schools will be closed February 18 for students and 10-mos staff. It’s a regular workday for 12-mos staff.

post_text: Guess who earned the highest possible ACT® composite score of 36? Lawrence High junior Arjun Agarwal! This achievement on the ACT is significant and rare. Less than one-half of 1% of all test takers earn the top score. Among US high school graduates in the Class of 2019, just 4,879 out of nearly 1.8 million students who took the ACT earned a composite score of 36. Awesome job, Arjun!
